## How Do Rules Work?

The incant parser, built into every field, is designed to process an
input stream. There is no lexer to run first and tokeninize the input;
the field parse does all that on its own. The input stream the field
parses is usually a big string loaded from a file, or maybe just a string
passed in when the field is invoked as a method. For example: field(argument);
invokes a field's method. The argument is of course a field that
can contain anything, but if the field is a rule, the argument must contain a
string to be used as its input stream. If there is no argument, as in: field();
That field rule reads its input stream from stdin, or more commonly, from a field
previously loaded from a file via incant's include command that loads an
input stream akin to stdin. The field parse ends on a parse error, or when the
parse reads the stop() command, or when the input stream ends.

An incant rule can contain data, no data, and/or a list of fields. It looks like
any incant field. When a field is added to a list, it is added as either an
attribute or a member, an option determined in field definition.

For a rule to succeed, if it has data, its data must match what is on the
input stream, and all its attributes must also match. The input stream cursor
is advanced on a match and holds tight on no match. If there is no match, and
the field list contains members, those members are tested in order, and if
any of them match, the parent field is considered a match as well, and the
member match result becomes the parent match result.

Essentially, a field, its attributes, and its members make up a rule tree.
Once the incant grammar is read in, the Start rule, defined in the grammar
file that is read in after the setup file, becomes the point of entry to the
incant language: one rule, and it, and its component rules define incant:
all the rules and rule components are fields; it is turtles all the way down.
