## Bootstrap Rule Details.

### The character matchers

```
counter=[0-9];
modifySet=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$];
nameSet=[a-zA-Z0-9];
```

These three rules each match a single character from a set. The `[...]` syntax is a
character set — same idea as a regular expression character class.

`counter` matches any digit. `nameSet` matches any letter or digit. `modifySet` matches
any of the special symbols that act as modifier characters in incant syntax — the `?`, `+`,
`*`, `@`, `^`, `}`, and others that you will see attached to rules throughout the bootstrap
list. Most of the modifiers will be familiar to anyone using a parser like yacc. They are
listed and defined below: (a full modifier reference appears in Appendix C.).

They don't do anything on their own. They exist so other rules can reference them.

---

### Building a number

```
PoweR=[eE] sign?=[+-] power=[0-9]+;
FloaT="." decimals=[0-9]+ PoweR?;
tokenize^@;
NumbeR=numberSet=[0-9]+ FloaT? tokenize;
```

`PoweR` matches a scientific notation exponent.

`FloaT` matches a decimal fraction: a literal dot, one or more digits, and an optional
exponent.

`NumbeR` matches a complete number: one or more digits, an optional `FloaT`. The tokenize
attribute makes everything the NumbeR rule matches look like a recognizable integer
or floating point number.

`tokenize` is unusual — it has no parsing definition of its own. It gathers all the
components of its parent rule as one string.

---

### Names and quoted strings

```
QuotE               tik=['"] quoteBody}=tik$@;
NamE                first-=[a-zA-Z] nameSet-^* tokenize;
```

`QuotE` matches a quoted string. It captures the opening quote character (either `'` or
`"`) into `tik`, then matches everything up to the matching closing quote.

`NamE` matches an identifier. It requires a letter first (`first-=[a-zA-Z]`), followed by
zero or more letters or digits (`nameSet-^*`). The tokenize attribute fires at the end
to concatenate the matched characters into the name that NamE returns.

---

### Groups, code blocks, and data

```
GrouP
    NamE;
    QuotE;

CodE                "{" "}" parseAction;

DatA
    GrouP;
    NumbeR;
    CodE;
    SetBrackets     '['- ']'};
    NotA=[^ \t\r\n;]+;
```

`GrouP` is rule with two options — it tries `NamE` first, then `QuotE`. The indented list
without colons is incant's way of writing alternatives: try each one in order until one
succeeds. A group is either a name or a quoted string.

`CodE` matches a `{ ... }` block that contains incant statements that at bootstrap incant
is not ready to deal with. The `parseAction` at the end is a hard-coded C++ method
that returns a string from { to } that will be passed lazily to the parser when needed;
that is, when a user invokes the field containing CodE as an action that needs to be
compiled (interpreted).

`DatA` is the most general data matcher — it tries five alternatives in order: a `GrouP`
(name or quoted string), a `NumbeR`, a `CodE` block, a `SetBrackets` character set
(`[...]`), or a `NotA` — anything that isn't whitespace or a semicolon. `DatA` is the
rule that answers "what kind of value can a field hold?" The answer is: any of these five
things.

---

### The structure rules — how a definition is built

This is where the bootstrap closes on itself. The following rules define what an incant
field definition looks like — and they are themselves field definitions.

```
Modifier=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$] noPrint;
TraiTdata           '='- DatA Modifier* Limit?;
TraiT               NamE Modifier* Limit? TraiTdata?;
Attributes=TraiT+;
Limit               '['- min=[0-9]+ max?=[0-9]+ ']'- noPrint;
MemberS             ':'- Mlist=DefinE+;
NewGroup            TraiT@;
```

A `Modifier` alters how the attribute it is associated with is parsed. Modifier definitions
are shown in Appendix C.

A `TraiT` is a name optionally followed by modifiers, an optional repeat `Limit`, and
optional `TraiTdata` (which is an `=` sign followed by a value). A trait is the basic
unit of a field definition — a name, its behavior flags, and optionally its data.

`Attributes` is one or more traits. When you write something like:

```
person name="Anthony" age=42;
```

`name="Anthony"` and `age=42` are both traits. Together they could be attributes of a
`person` field.

`Limit` matches a `[min max]` repeat constraint — the `[0-9]+` in many rules above is
shorthand for "one or more," which is a limit with min=1.

`MemberS` matches the member list of a field — a colon followed by one or more `DefinE`
rules. This is where fields nest: a field's members are themselves full field definitions.
Note: the colon is required in the MemberS rule, but the user never types it.
Incant's parser has no separate lexer — it processes the input stream character by
character in a single pass. When it skips whitespace (spaces, tabs, newlines) looking
for the next field, it inserts the structural colon automatically. Indentation is how
you signal nesting; the colon is the parser's way of recording it.

`NewGroup` is a rule that essentially just wraps the result TraiT delivers with the name
NewGroup.

---

### DefinE — the rule that defines all rules

```
DefinE;
DefinE              NewGroup Attributes? MemberS? endDefine-=[;>];
```

`DefinE` appears twice. The first line is a forward declaration — a bare name with
nothing but a semicolon. It says: this rule exists. Trust me. Details to follow.

This is necessary because `MemberS` references `DefinE` (a member list is a list of
`DefinE` rules), and `DefinE` references `MemberS`. Each one needs the other. The forward
declaration breaks the chicken-and-egg problem the same way a C++ forward declaration
does — no special keyword needed, just a placeholder with the same shape as the real
thing.

The second `DefinE` is the full definition. A complete field definition consists of:

- A `NewGroup` — the name and opening trait
- Optional `Attributes` — zero or more name=value pairs
- Optional `MemberS` — a nested member list
- `endDefine` — which matches either `;` or `>` to close the definition

`endDefine` with the `-` modifier means the closing character is consumed but not kept.
`=[;>]` means it accepts either a semicolon or a `>` as the terminator. As with the
colon in the MemberS rule, `>` is never entered, it is provided via indenting.

This single rule — `DefinE` — is what allows everything in incant to be defined in incant
syntax. When you write `person name="Anthony" age=42;`, `DefinE` is the rule that
recognizes and processes it.

---

### DEFINing and clean indentation

```
define              DEFINing- definitions=DefinE+ DEFINing- ';'-;
```

The `define` rule wraps a block of `DefinE` rules. The `DEFINing` on each side is a
command that sets a flag in the runtime. That flag tells the pretty-printer it is inside a
definition block, which is how incant definitions get their clean Python-like indentation.
The language cares about how it looks — not as an afterthought, but baked into the parsing
machinery from the start.

---

### The housekeeping rules

```
debug               "ALL"? "GUARD"? rules=NamE* ';'-;
InvokE              '('- NamE? ')'-;
RunRulE             NamE InvokE? ';'-?;
InitiatE=RunRulE+;
```

`debug` turns on diagnostic output. The optional `ALL` keyword enables additional output. If `GUARD` is provided, it turns on debugging for rule guards. If no rules are specified, all rules are debugged.

`InvokE` matches the `(name)` call syntax used when invoking a rule as a method.

`RunRulE` matches a single rule invocation: a name, an optional `InvokE`, and an optional
semicolon. It's how incant runs things when only bootstrap rules are available to run on.

`InitiatE` is one or more `RunRulE` invocations. It's the entry point — the rule that
reads and executes the startup sequence when incant launches.

