## Modifiers

Modifiers are single characters that appear after a rule name (or after its `=data`) in a definition. They change how the rule matches — how many times it must match, whether it consumes input, whether it labels its result, and so on. The modifier characters are drawn from `modifySet`:

```
modifySet=[-~+?!%&|*@_<^{}$];
```

More than one modifier can follow a single rule reference, in any order.

| Modifier | Name | Effect |
|----------|------|--------|
| `+` | one-or-more | The rule must match at least once; repeats as many times as it can. |
| `*` | zero-or-more | The rule may match zero times; repeats as many times as it can. |
| `?` | optional | The rule may match zero or one time. Failure is not an error. |
| `!` | bang | Inverts match sense — succeeds where the rule would fail, fails where it would succeed. |
| `-` | no-label | The matched value is consumed but not stored. Used for punctuation that must be present but isn't data. |
| `^` | no-skip | Suppresses whitespace skipping before this match. The parser normally skips spaces, tabs, and newlines between rule elements; `^` turns that off for this element. |
| `<` | no-advance | Matches without consuming input. The cursor stays where it is after a successful match. Useful for lookahead. |
| `@` | target | Marks this element as the target — the result the parent rule returns. |
| `_` | unguarded | Bypasses the rule's guard check. |
| `{` | up-to | Matches everything up to (but not including) the rule's match. Implies unguarded. |
| `}` | up-to-over | Matches everything up to and including the rule's match. Implies unguarded. |
| `&` | pointer | Treats the matched value as a pointer reference rather than a copy. |
| `$` | macro | Marks this element as a macro expansion point. |

The remaining members of `modifySet` — `%`, `|`, and `~` — currently have no effect in the
modifier processor. (`%` has an implemented behavior but is not used anywhere, so "no
effect" holds in practice.) They are present in the set and reserved for future use.

A few modifiers combine naturally. `+` and `*` both set `max` to unlimited; `*` also sets `min` to zero. So `nameSet-^*` means: match zero or more characters from `nameSet`, suppress whitespace skipping (`^`), and don't label the result (`-`). Three modifiers, any order, one tight match expression.

The `-` modifier deserves special mention because it appears constantly throughout the bootstrap rules. Every piece of required syntax that isn't data gets `-`: the `'='` in `TraiTdata`, the `'['` and `']'` in `SetBrackets` and `Limit`, the `'('` and `')'` in `InvokE`. The rule must see it — but it doesn't become part of the result.

