## Rule Actions

A rule matching its input does not, by itself, do anything. The match succeeds or fails — that is all. To make something happen when a rule matches, you attach a rule action: a piece of C++ code that fires the moment the match completes.

Most bootstrap rules have no action. They match, they return what they matched, done. But a few rules need to do real work — work that cannot be expressed as pattern matching alone. Those rules have actions, and without them incant would not get off the ground.

### NamE — building a label, and something more

In most languages, before you can use a variable you must declare it. You tell the compiler its name and type, and the compiler reserves space for it. Incant has no declarations. A field comes into existence the first time it is named — and `aCTionNamE` is where that happens.

```
NamE    first-=[a-zA-Z] nameSet-^* tokenize;
```

`NamE` matches an identifier: one letter, then zero or more letters-or-digits. The `-` modifiers mean none of those characters are individually labeled — they are consumed but not kept as separate results. `tokenize` fires at the end and stitches the characters back together into a single string. Without it, matching `Anthony` would consume seven characters and produce nothing a caller could use.

That is the matching half. The action half is where things get interesting.

When `aCTionNamE` fires, it takes the assembled name and looks it up in the current method — `locateInMethod`. If it finds a field with that name, that field becomes the result. Normal enough.

But if no field is found, and the action is firing inside a code block being compiled (`processingCode`), incant does not fail. It creates a new field with that name, attaches it to the current action as a local, and returns it. The field now exists because it was named.

This is incant's no-declaration model at its root. There is no `var`, no `int`, no `count` declaration required. Writing a new name inside an action body is the declaration. The parser sees the name, finds nothing, and quietly builds the field on the spot — marked `isLocal`, attached to the action, ready to use.

`DefinE`'s action builds fields from explicit definitions. `NamE`'s action builds fields from mere mention. Together they cover the two ways a field comes into existence in incant.

---

### DefinE — making definitions do something

```
DefinE    NewGroup Attributes? MemberS? endDefine-=[;>];
```

When `DefinE` matches, it has recognized the shape of a field definition. But recognition alone does not create a field. `aCTionDefinE` fires after the match and does the real work — and there is quite a lot of it.

**Registry wiring.** If there is a current registry when the definition is processed, the new field gets added to it automatically. You do not register things explicitly. Defining a field inside a registry context is registration. The act of definition and the act of registration are the same act.

**Attributes as immediate actions.** Most attributes get stored on the new field — they become its data. But some attributes are marked `noPrint` and carry an `immediateACTION` flag. Those do not get stored. They get *run*, right then, during the definition itself. A command can execute at define time rather than at call time. This is how things like `register()` and `initFORMs()` work when they appear as attributes in a definition block — they are not declarations, they are invocations wearing declaration syntax.

**Code attachment and lazy compilation.** If the definition includes a code block, incant does not compile it immediately. Instead it sets `isCoded` on the new field and parks the raw code string. The first time something invokes that field as an action, `processCode` fires and the code gets compiled then. The field is live and usable before its code is ever looked at.

**The hidden locals.** When a code block is present, `aCTionDefinE` quietly adds two fields to the new field before anyone touches the code: `this` — a reference back to the field itself — and `tempField` — a scratch field used by operators to hold intermediate results. The programmer never writes these. They are simply there, every time, in every action body. `this` is how an action refers to itself. `tempField` is how `opPlus` and its siblings return a value without modifying either operand.

**Method discovery by naming convention.** If the new field is a rule, incant looks for a C++ function whose name is `aCTion` followed by the field's tag — `aCTionNamE`, `aCTionDefinE`, `aCTionExpressioN`, and so on. It finds them via `dlsym`, the same mechanism the operating system uses to locate symbols in loaded libraries. If the function exists, it gets wired as the rule's method automatically. No registration table. No explicit binding. The naming convention *is* the binding.

This last mechanism closes a loop that might otherwise seem mysterious: how does a bootstrap rule written in C++ connect to the incant grammar that names it? The answer is that it does not need to be connected. It just needs to be named correctly. When `DefinE` processes the `NamE` rule definition, it looks for `aCTionNamE`, finds it in the binary, and wires it. The C++ and the incant grammar meet at the name.

Every field you define in incant, every registry entry, every operator binding, every rule in the grammar — all of it passes through `aCTionDefinE` on the way to existence. It is the most consequential action in the bootstrap, and most of what it does is invisible to the programmer writing definitions.

---

### parseAction — deferred compilation

```
CodE    "{" "}" parseAction;
```

`CodE` matches a `{ ... }` block. But at bootstrap time, incant is not yet ready to compile and run arbitrary code — the language isn't fully defined yet. So `CodE`'s action does something deliberately minimal: it captures everything between the braces as a raw string and stores it on the field, untouched.

Later, when something actually invokes that field as an action, the stored string gets handed to the compiler. The work happens then, not at parse time.

This is lazy evaluation baked into the bootstrap. It is how incant can parse code blocks it isn't yet equipped to run — and it is why you can write action bodies in incant syntax before the full language exists to interpret them.
